        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We are aiming at resolving 1000AU scales which results in a spatial
resolution requirement of 0.5''. Our sensitivity estimate is based on
the following rationale: The peak flux at 870mum observed with the
ATLASGAL survey (Schuller et al. 2009) is 52Jy/beam with a beam size
of 19.2''. Assuming a nu^4 power-law relation for the fluxes at
(sub)mm wavelengths between 870mum and 1.3mm, we expect a flux of
10.8Jy per 19'' area in ALMAs band 6. With previous interferometers
like the PdBI or SMA, we typically filtered out 90% of the single-dish
flux. While the superior uv-coverage of ALMA will most likely recover
significantly more flux, we conservatively still assume that only 10%
or about 1Jy flux will be observed from our source. Typical
polarization ratios of dust continuum emission in star-forming regions
are between 1 and 5% (e.g., Beuther et al. 2010). Hence, again
conservatively we can expect a polarized flux of at least 10mJy or
more. Assuming the most extreme case that the flux is homogeneously
distributed over the source size of 5'', we would have &gt;0.1mJy per
0.5'' beam polarized flux. Since the time requirement for polarization
observations is 3 hours because of sufficient parallactic angle
coverage, we find that within this 3 hours a continuum rms of 0.014mJy
will be achieved. With our conservative estimates and &gt;0.1Jy/beam
expected polarized flux, even this scenario results in a &gt;7sigma
detection for over 100 resolution elements. In addition to this, with
a larger fraction of recovered emission by ALMA, a different than
uniform flux distribution and a larger polarization fraction, also
larger final polarized fluxes are expected. Therefore, our proposed
observations will very sensitively probe the polarization and by that
magnetic field within this high-mass star-forming region.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
