    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Magnetic fields play a central role during star formation in general and high-mass star formation in particular. They serve on the one hand as a break and can slow down the collapse motion of the dense gas. On the other hand, magnetic fields are required to drive the collimated jets that are also observed around high-mass protostars. In spite of this importance, current observational knowledge about the magnetic field structure in dense, massive gas cores is scarce. This is largely because the sensitivity of previous interferometers was not sufficient to observe the magnetic field for many sources at sufficient depth. ALMA now opens a new window for magnetic field studies with its order of magnitude increase in sensitivity. Therefore, here we propose to investigate the magnetic field structure of one prototypical high-luminosity (10^5 Lsun) region that is known for its rotational and outflow properties. With this ALMA data we can map the magnetic field morphology and derive the magnetic field strength in this region. These observables will be set into context with the predictions of classical ambipolar diffusion theory as well as models that are more dominated by turbulent motions.</prp:abstract>
    <prp:relatedProposals>There is an accompanying proposal by the same PI to study the infall, rotation and inner outflow properties of this region in the 690GHz band.</prp:relatedProposals>
